%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% ROBUSTNESS %%%%%%%%%%%%%%% 

\subsubsection{Robustness Analysis}
To verify the robustness of our models to out-of-distribution data,
we evaluated our features on ImageNet-A(dversarial) (\texttt{Im-A})~\cite{hendrycks2021natural}, ImageNet-R(endition) (\texttt{Im-R})~\cite{hendrycks2021many},
ImageNet-C(orruptions) (\texttt{Im-C})~\cite{hendrycks2018benchmarking},
ImageNet-Sketch (\texttt{Sketch})~\cite{wang2019learningrobust},
ImageNet ReaL (\texttt{Real})~\cite{beyer2020imagenetreal} and
ImageNet-V2 (\texttt{V2})~\cite{recht2019imagenetv2}. The results for finetuned models and models with linear classification, which follow the protocol outlined above, are presented in Tables~\ref{tab:robustness-sup} and~\ref{tab:robustness-linear}.
We report the mean corruption error (\texttt{mCE}) on ImageNet-C, ReaL accuracy on ImageNet ReaL and top-1 accuracy on the rest of the datasets. For baselines marked with an asterisk (\texttt{*}), we present the results available in the referenced paper.

In the finetuned setting, {\OPENOURS} and {\OURS} models outperform the best models on all the robustness benchmarks, on some of them (Im-A, Im-R, Im-C, Sketch) by a large margin.
The results in linear classification setting show that {\OPENOURS} and {\OURS} models scale well and yield significant performance gains on Im-A and Im-C benchmarks.

