%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% DAVIS %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\subsection{Video instance segmentation.} 
% \pb{POC: Amir}
We evaluate our frozen \OURS~patch features on the DAVIS-2017 benchmark for video object segmentation~\cite{pont20172017}. Following previous testing protocols~\cite{jabri2020space,caron2021emerging}, given a semantic segmentation of the first frame in a video, we use k-nearest neighbors between patches of consecutive video frames to label the rest of the video. To compare with DINO~\cite{caron2021emerging} that utilizes ViT-B with 8x8 patch size, we evaluate \OPENOURS-H on x2 resolution images (960p). Finally, we evaluate the predicted segmentations against the ground truth and report the similarity in terms of mean IOU ($\mathcal{J}_m$), the mean alignment between the boundaries of the mask ($\mathcal{F_m}$), and the average of the too ($\mathcal{J\&F}_m$). The results in Table~\ref{tab:dense} shows an improvement of 1\% in $\mathcal{J\&F}_m$  compared to DINO (ViT-B). This shows that scaling the model size and data provides improved patch level representations.


\begin{table}[t]
  \centering
