\section{Environmental Impact}

The experiments we have run have a high environmental cost.
They were conducted using a private infrastructure and AWS, and we estimate total emissions to be in the order of a thousand tons of CO$_2$eq (the equivalent of several full transatlantic planes). 
The main sources of emissions are the self-supervised pre-training of the models, and the finetuning evaluations on the downstream tasks.
For example, a single pre-training of a ViT-G model (30k GPU-hours) emits 2 tons of CO$_2$eq, and a finetuning on ImageNet-1k (1k GPU-hours) emits 0.1 tons.
Estimations were conducted using the \href{https://mlco2.github.io/impact#compute}{Machine Learning Impact calculator} presented by  Lacoste~\etal~\cite{lacoste2019quantifying}. It should be noted that this estimate only takes into account the electricity consumption of the GPUs used, and as such it ignores other emissions, in particular the emissions incurred during the rest of the GPU lifecycles.

This environmental impact is mitigated in several ways:
\begin{itemize}
\item \OURS{}  can be used as a universal feature extractor. 
The models we trained - and that we will open source - can be used for several downstream tasks, reducing the need of specialized architectures and their training.
\item We advocate the use of linear evaluations with frozen backbones as an alternative to heavy finetunings.
In our case, we show results close to the state-of-the-art (sometimes higher) with just a linear head.
\item We point out the importance of optimizing the memory consumption and efficiency of the models.
\end{itemize}
